INSERT INTO `text_box` VALUES ('ACCOUNTABILITY','CHRONIC','Chronic diseases are often interrelated, which means public health prevention strategies can potentially impact multiple health outcomes. Targeted, evidence-based approaches are most likely to have a significant effect on preventing and improving management of chronic diseases.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nSpringfield-Greene County Health Department employed Community Health Workers to work with members of their communities in an effort to monitor and lower high blood pressure. Public health partner [Jordan Valley Community Health Center|https://www.news-leader.com/story/news/local/ozarks/2019/09/12/jordan-valley-community-health-workers-healthcare-financial-resources/2214214001/] now employs Community Health Workers that help residents live healthier lives.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Cost-Effectiveness of High Blood Pressure Interventions, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/programs-impact/pop/high-blood-pressure.htm]\r\n[Cost-Effectiveness of Diabetes Interventions, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/programs-impact/pop/diabetes.htm]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('ACCOUNTABILITY','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','Public health agencies must have the capacity to continuously monitor, measure, and assure performance standards for communicable disease prevention and control. This foundational capability must be in place in every Missouri community in order to ensure a functional public health system statewide.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Measuring What Matters in Public Health, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/uploads/downloadable-resources/NACCHO-PM-System-Guide.pdf]\r\n[Developing a Performance Assessment Framework and Indicators for Communicable Disease Management in Natural Disasters|https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26652758/]\r\n[Infectious Disease Objectives, Healthy People 2020|https://health.gov/healthypeople/objectives-and-data/browse-objectives/infectious-disease]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('ACCOUNTABILITY','ENVIRONMENT','NACCHO partnered with CDC in 2000 to create the Protocol for Assessing Community Excellence in Environmental Health (PACE EH). The guide equips public health leaders and their partners to complete a community-level environmental public health assessment.\r\nThis methodology guides communities and local health officials in conducting community-based environmental health assessments. It invites the public and stakeholders to engage in identifying local environmental public health issues, establish local priorities, and prioritize actions for populations at highest risk.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Improving Environmental Public Health Services Performance to Meet Community Needs, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/envphps/docs/improving-eph-serv-perf-comm.pdf]\r\n[Protocol for Assessing Community Excellence in Environmental Health, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/ceha/pace_eh.htm]\r\n[Environmental Public Health Performance Standards, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/envphps/default.htm]\r\n[10 Essential Environmental Public Health Services, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/10-essential-services/index.html]\r\n[Local Assessment and Governance Tools, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-infrastructure/performance-improvement/community-health-assessment/local-assessment-and-governance-tools]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('ACCOUNTABILITY','INJURY','PerÂ­forÂ­mance manÂ­ageÂ­ment is the conÂ­tinÂ­uÂ­ous process of improvÂ­ing perÂ­forÂ­mance by setÂ­ting goals aligned with the agency\'s strateÂ­gic goals, setting tasks to achieve the goals, reviewÂ­ing and evaluating progress, and develÂ­opÂ­ing the knowlÂ­edge, skills and abilÂ­iÂ­ties of employees to carry out the work.\r\nFor decades public health has worked to prevent injuries by identifying risks and causes and working to mitigate them. Two areas in which public health have seen success are in motorcycle injury prevention and access to clean needles. CDC lists these two interventions among its [HI-5|https://www.cdc.gov/policy/hst/hi5/interventions/] list of interventions that can make a significant impact on population health within five years. Quality improvement in injury prevention includes analyzing trends in injuries and violence, building collaboration between emergency medicine and public health, and increasing the use of screening to mitigate high-risk health behaviors.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/injury/index.html]\r\n[We Can Prevent Adverse Childhood Experiences, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/injury/features/adverse-childhood-experiences/]\r\n[America\'s Drug Overdose Epidemic: Putting Data to Action, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/injury/features/prescription-drug-overdose/index.html]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Injury Prevention'),('ACCOUNTABILITY','LINKAGE','To increase trust between public health and its community partners, public health must assure a culture of accountability for their performance. They must demonstrate to partners the use of data-driven measures to guide decision making and improve program outcomes. The process begins with the creation of agency and cross-agency priority goals, development of a strategic plan, and implementation of regular performance reviews. Public health experts should lead in this effort as chief health strategists for their community.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Becoming a Community Chief Health Strategist, Public Health Foundation|http://www.phf.org/consulting/Pages/Becoming_the_Community_Chief_Health_Strategist.aspx]\r\n[Prepare and Support our Chief Health Strategists on the Front Lines, American Journal of Public Health|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5508177/]\r\n[Policy Paper: The Local Health Department as Chief Health Strategist, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/uploads/downloadable-resources/15-11-LHD-as-Community-Chief-Health-Strategist.pdf]\r\n[The High Achieving Health Department in 2020, Resolve|https://www.resolve.ngo/docs/the-high-achieving-governmental-health-department-as-the-chief-health-strategist-by-2020-final1636869407709140046.pdf]\r\n[Improving Organizational Management and Development, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/improve-organizational-management-and-development]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('ACCOUNTABILITY','MATERNAL','Public health seeks to influence public health attitudes and behaviors among parents and caregivers. They play a vital role in the health and well-being of their children, older family members, and people with chronic health conditions or disabilities. Public health agencies should continuously assess their own capacity to create healthy environments for all Missourians, encourage preventive health care visits, and teach healthy habits.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Parents or Caregivers Objectives, Healthy People 2030|https://health.gov/healthypeople/objectives-and-data/browse-objectives/parents-or-caregivers]\r\n[The Health and Family Planning Manager\'s Toolkit, Management Services for Health|https://www.msh.org/sites/default/files/performance-management-tool.pdf]','Accountability and Performance Management intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('ASSESSMENT','CHRONIC','Local, state and national surveillance systems collect data on many health indicators, including chronic diseases and their risk factors. These data help public health professionals better understand how chronic diseases are affecting community members, what common risk factors or causes need to be addressed, and how limited resources can best be put to use.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nIn the mid-1990s, a health study conducted in Joplin showed 14 percent of children had elevated levels of lead in their blood from ingesting dust and soil contaminated with lead. A public education campaign that stressed hand washing and the importance of blood testing by local pediatricians, among other things, was launched. [Yards were excavated and replaced with cleaner soil|https://www.joplinglobe.com/news/local_news/426-joplin-yards-test-high-for-lead-levels-after-being-disturbed-by-tornado/article_65a2d545-7362-5b00-a935-2dbee73ca092.html], and a subsequent health study showed that the lead-poisoning rate among Joplinâs children had fallen to 2 percent, which at the time was close to the national average.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Using Surveillance Systems to Prevent and Control Chronic Diseases, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/resources/infographic/surveillance-systems.htm]','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('ASSESSMENT','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','Public health communicable disease nurses continuously engage in assessment and surveillance activities in order to rapidly identify potential disease outbreaks in their community. Both active and passive surveillance systems alert nurses to high rates of absenteeism at schools and at large employers. Surveillance in partnership with local pharmacies alerts nurses to an increase in sales of over-the-counter medications that may signal an outbreak of illness. Hospital surveillance of chief complaint or triage codes alerts public health to potential outbreaks, as well.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[How Counting Disease Cases Prompts Action, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/surveillance/pdfs/Counting-disease-casesh.pdf]\r\n[Public Health Surveillance: Preparing for the Future, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/surveillance/pdfs/Surveillance-Series-Bookleth.pdf]\r\n[Improving Public Health Surveillance and Data, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/surveillance/pdfs/Surveillance-Series-Bookleth.pdf]','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('ASSESSMENT','ENVIRONMENT','The Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry (ATSDR) assesses hazardous waste sites to determine when public health actions need to be taken to prevent people living nearby from being exposed to toxic substances. Public health agencies should have a similar capacity to assess the impact on public health of any hazardous substance in the environment, issue health advisories and recommendations, and identify policies or programs necessary to assess or prevent public health impacts.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nIn 2010, after a routine water test in the Rogersville, Missouri area found [traces of TCE|https://www.epa.gov/mo/compass-plaza-well-trichloroethylene-tce-superfund-site-rogersville-missouri-fact-sheet-august#:~:text=The%20Compass%20Plaza%20Well%20TCE,in%20and%20around%20Rogersville%2C%20Missouri.&text=Environmental%20sampling%20has%20found%20TCE,two%20non%2Dcommunity%20public%20wells.], the Springfield-Greene County Health Department was asked to work with local and federal partners to help identify the scope and impact of the contamination.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Public Health Assessment Guidance Manual, ATSDR|https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/hac/phamanual/pdfs/phagm_final1-27-05.pdf]\r\n[Public Health Assessment Training, ATSDR|https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/training/public-health-assessment-overview/html/index.html]','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('ASSESSMENT','INJURY','Injury surveillance requires specific public health skills in epidemiology, cross-jurisdictional and multi-disciplinary collaboration with local, state, and regional partners, and evidence-based strategies to mitigate upstream or common causes.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nParnters in the St. Louis area collaborate through the [Injury Free Coalition for Kids of St. Louis|https://www.injuryfree.org/site_display.cfm?PermanentId=34118511-EE98-4241-A18E2F3C4055C59E]. St. Louis Children\'s Hospital created two programs focused on community-based injury prevention education and providing safe and constructive environments for children.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Injury Surveillance Training Guide, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/pdf/participant-guide.pdf]\r\n[Reducing the Burden of Injury: Advancing and Treatment; Surveillance and Data, Institute of Medicine Committee on Injury Prevention and Control|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK230576/]\r\n','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Injury Prevention'),('ASSESSMENT','LINKAGE','Public health surveillance is defined by the World Health Organization as the \"ongoing, systematic collection, analysis and interpretation of health-related data essential to the planning, implementation, and evaluation of public health practice.\"\r\nSurveillance helps public health experts identify potential public health emergencies and informs development of policies and intervention strategies. With surveillance acting as an early warning signal, public health can convene partners to begin planning actions needed to prevent disease transmission, control outbreaks, and reduce the loss of life and the economic impact.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nThe [Webster County commissioners convened a local task force|https://webstercountymo.gov/covid-19/] in Marshfield, Missouri in December 2020 in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. Members of the task force were responsible to provide data, information, and updates to guide the commissioners\' decision-making related to policies and activities that might be necessary in response to COVID-19.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Public Health Surveillance: A Tool for Targeting and Monitoring Interventions, Nsubuga P, White ME, Thacker SB|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK11770/]\r\n[Public Health Surveillance, WHO|https://www.who.int/immunization/monitoring_surveillance/burden/vpd/en/]\r\n[Referral Systems Assessment and Monitoring Toolkit, Measure Evaluation|https://www.measureevaluation.org/resources/publications/ms-13-60/at_download/document]\r\n','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('ASSESSMENT','MATERNAL','Needs assessments examine data and trends over time to identify historical context, the current baseline, progress, and areas for improvement. Maternal, child health assessments are required every five years through the Title V program. Through assessment and surveillance, health inequities can be identified and eliminated, allowing all of us to live our healthiest lives.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[MCH Needs Assessment Toolkit, National MCH Workforce Development Center|https://www.mchneeds.net/]\r\n[MCH Needs Assessment Training, Association of Maternal and Child Health Programs|http://www.amchp.org/AboutTitleV/Resources/Pages/NeedsAssessmentResources.aspx]\r\n[Addressing Health Equity in Public Health Practice: Frameworks, Promising Strategies, and Measurement Considerations, CDC|https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/abs/10.1146/annurev-publhealth-040119-094119]\r\n[Paving the Road to Health Equity, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/minorityhealth/publications/health_equity/index.html]\r\n[Strengthening the Science and Practice of Health Equity in Public Health, CDC|http://journals.lww.com/jphmp/Fulltext/2016/01001/Strengthening_the_Science_and_Practice_of_Health.1.aspx]','Assessment and Surveillance intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('ASSESSMENTS','INJURY','add text','Assessment and Surveillance and Injury Prevention'),('ASSESSMENTS','LINKAGE','add text here','Assessment and Surveillance and Linkage to Care'),('ASSESSMENTS','MATERNAL','hellooo ','Hello some text'),('COMMUNICATIONS','CHRONIC','In order to reduce the burden of chronic disease on communities and the healthcare system, people with chronic disease must be involved in their own healthcare, significantly contributing to decision-making and disease management. Clear communication helps patients better understand their chronic disease and increases compliance. It also positively affects their confidence, satisfaction with healthcare, and quality of life.\r\nCommunicators must clearly explain to the public the risks of chronic disease, the health impacts, and strategies for disease prevention and management. With effective communication, public health can reduce the burden of chronic disease on communities, reduce healthcare costs, and save lives.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nThe Columbia-Boone County Health Department in Missouri launched its [Live Well by Faith|https://www.como.gov/health/live-well-by-faith/] program in response to higher rates of high blood pressure and diabetes disease and death among Black residents. In a unique partnership with area churches, public health professionals provide information and programs that empower people to address their own chronic disease issues.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Five Communication Strategies to Promote Self-Management of Chronic Illness, American Academy of Family Physicians|https://www.aafp.org/fpm/2009/0900/p12.html]\r\n[Communication as the Basis of Care for Patients with Chronic Diseases, American Journal of Nursing Science|http://article.nursingscience.net/pdf/10.11648.j.ajns.s.2018070301.12.pdf]','Communications intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('COMMUNICATIONS','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','In a disaster, the most important thing people want to know in an emergency is how to protect themselves and their family. Successful communication must be timely, accurate, and credible. It must answer people\'s concerns and provide clear guidance. Failure to communicate well can confuse the public, lead to the perception that public health agencies are not prepared, and actually exacerbate the threat.\r\nGood risk communication should be transparent and build trust with the audience. It should provide them science-based information they need to make the best possible decisions in the moment about their health and well-being.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nThe 2020 COVID-19 pandemic presented an unprecedented challenge for communications. Public health agencies failed repeatedly to disseminate timely, accurate, credible information that penetrated the \"noise\" of traditional and social media. Changing information, inconsistent messaging from multiple sources, and the [audience\'s sense of hazard and outrage|https://academic.oup.com/cid/advance-article/doi/10.1093/cid/ciaa758/5858208] made the public information response extremely difficult.\r\nDuring the Ebola outbreak in 2014, exaggerated media coverage of the two healthcare workers infected in the US left many people unneccesarily fearful of exposure. In Dallas special permits were issued and a biohazard team deployed to assure an entire apartment complex was cleaned after a [man being treated for Ebola|https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ebola-virus-outbreak/no-excuse-cleanup-starts-after-delay-ebola-victims-apartment-n217776] vomitted in the parking lot.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Communicating the Threat of Emerging Infections to the Public, CDC|https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/6/4/00-0403_article]\r\n[Communications Resources for Public Health Professionals, Public Health Communications Collaborative|https://publichealthcollaborative.org/]\r\n[Communicating about Infectious Disease Threats: Insights from Public Health Information Officers, Science Direct|https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0363811118303382]','Communications intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('COMMUNICATIONS','ENVIRONMENT','Communicating about the real and perceived risks in areas of environmental public health, such as food, air, water, wastewater, and chemicals, creates a unique challenge for public health professionals. People understand how contaminants or toxins affect health, but when asked about \"environmental health\" they often think about how we affect our environment, not how it affects public health.\r\nEffective communication about environmental public health issues should address the audience\'s concerns. Their response to information will depend on their individual perceptions, experiences, and trust in the messenger. Information should be delivered in multiple formats so that it is accessible, understandable, and actionable for everyone. \r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nThe anthrax attacks of 2001 created an increase in public concern, fueled by [media reports|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4629804/] of \"white powder\" incidents. Public health agencies received an influx of calls from concerned citizens who discovered white powder in kitchens, bathrooms, and other places that were easily explained and non-threatening.\r\nWhen West Nile virus gained public attention in the early 2000s, public health agencies received a significant increase in the number of requests for dead bird collection and testing. Local public health agenices in the greater St. Louis area collaborated on a [West Nile Virus response plan|https://www.sccmo.org/DocumentCenter/View/724/St-Louis-Metro-Area-Action-Plan-PDF-?bidId=], including a public information and education component.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Environmental Public Health, APHA|https://www.apha.org/topics-and-issues/environmental-health]\r\n[Healthy Community Design (strategies for communicating about environmental public health), APHA|https://apha.org/topics-and-issues/environmental-health/healthy-community-design]\r\n[Building and Understanding of Environmental Health, FrameWorks Institute|https://www.frameworksinstitute.org/toolkit/building-understanding-of-environmental-health/]\r\n[Upstream, Downstream (video), FrameWorks Institute|https://vimeo.com/105682562]\r\n[Risk Communication: Evolution to Revolution, P. Sandman and V. Covello|http://www.psandman.com/articles/covello.htm]\r\n\r\nTraining:\r\n[Effective Communication for Environmental Public Health, Northwest Center for Public Health Practice|https://www.nwcphp.org/training/effective-communication-for-environmental-public-health]\r\n','Communications intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('COMMUNICATIONS','INJURY','A person\'s perception of risk guides decision-making about activities or behaviors that may lead to injury. Communicators must understand the \'mental models\' people form explain how they perceive risk and understand the value of prevention. Evidence shows communication that uses clear, action-based messages helps to close the gap between true and perceived risk and lead to behavior change and injury prevention. \r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nTo prevent motor vehicle accident injuries, Missouri first adopted the national \"Click it or ticket\" campaign in 2014. The campaign seeks to increase awareness of the benefit of wearing a seat belt. In its 2019 report, the Missouri Department of Transportation said [seat belt use had steadily increased|https://www.modot.org/node/18773] in Missouri over the past three years to 87.7% in 2019, just under the national average of 90.7%.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Using communication theory in injury prevention campaigns, Injury Prevention|https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22088928/]\r\n[Cardiff Violence Prevention Model: External Communications and Media Relations, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/publichealthissue/fundedprograms/cardiffmodel/external.html]','Communications intersect with Injury Prevention'),('COMMUNICATIONS','LINKAGE','Public health agencies will not be able to provide every service needed by community members, but they can develop a strong network of partners and an effective referral system that assures people access to the services they need. An important component of communication in linking people to services is effective listening skills. Rather than anticipating or making assumptions about needs, communicators must listen carefully and then shape communication and referrals around the person\'s concerns, needs, or goals. A second important component in the success of linkage to care is clear communication between public health as the sender and its partners as the receiver of the individual.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nMasachusetts created an online screening tool to help begin conversations about what people need. At [helpsteps.com|https://www.helpsteps.com/hs/home/#/] community members can search for the resources they need by topic, or they can fill out a short survey that provides a self-screening to help them identify their own needs.\r\nIn 2017, New York City Health + Hospitals piloted a process to [screen patients for social determinants of health|https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/10.2105/AJPH.2020.305642]. Their goal was to refer patients to non-clinical and community based resources.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Referral System Defined, WHO|https://www.who.int/management/Referralnotes.doc]\r\n[Referral System in Health Care, S.A. Tabish|https://www.researchgate.net/publication/261957501_Referral_System_in_Health_Care]\r\n[Screening Tool, New York City Health + Hospitals|https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/suppl/10.2105/AJPH.2020.305642/suppl_file/berry_supplemental_appendix_f.pdf]\r\n[PHRASES: Using Message Framing Tools to Build and Sustain Cross-Sector Partnerships|https://www.r4phtc.org/phrases-using-message-framing-tools-to-build-and-sustain-cross-sector-partnerships/]','Communications intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('COMMUNICATIONS','MATERNAL','Research shows women with higher self-efficacy - or belief in her own capacity to control her motivation, behavior, and social environment - more assertively communicate about health risks and behaviors with family members. By targeting women as a primary audience in communication about public health issues, communicators are more likely to affect the health of women, children and families.\r\nEffective communication with women depends on the communicator\'s ability to listen effectively, share information clearly, and consider how culture, literacy level, language, and ability may affect communication. \r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Being Heard: Key Communication Strategies for Maternal and Child Health Organizations, US Breastfeeding Committee|http://www.usbreastfeeding.org/p/cm/ld/fid=251&tid=552&sid=1194]\r\n[Supporting Breastfeeding Interventions for Faith-Based Organizations, USAID (also applicable for US interventions)|https://sbccimplementationkits.org/fbo-breastfeeding/courses/supporting-breastfeeding-interventions-for-faith-based-organizations/]\r\n\r\nTraining:\r\n[Health Communication, Tulane University School of Public Health (requires account creation)|https://lms.southcentralpartnership.org/course/viewguest.php?id=247]\r\n[Communicating With and For the Maternal and Child Health Population: Issues and Challenges, Tulane University School of Public Health (requires account creation)|https://lms.southcentralpartnership.org/course/viewguest.php?id=190]\r\n[The Messenger Chronicles: Effective Communication Strategies for Difficult Conversations, MCH Navigator (requires account set up)|https://www.mchnavigator.org/trainings/1270-messenger-chronicles.php]','Communications intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('COMMUNITY','CHRONIC','The burden of chronic disease in Missouri continues to grow, yet many of these chronic diseases are preventable with lifestyle changes. Public health agencies increasingly collaborate with community members and partners to build environments where the healthy choice is the easy choice. Their work is evidenced by more fresh fruits and vegetables available in food deserts, by sidewalks and bike lanes in cities, by chronic disease management education, and by smoke-free buildings and spaces.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nLincoln and Montgomery County Health Departments partner to deliver fresh fruits and vegetables to rural communities with limited access to grocery stores through their [Harvest Hauler|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/050418_Harvest_Hauler_Lincoln.pdf] - a Farmers\' Market on wheels.\r\nColumbia-Boone County Health Department worked with their local housing authority and residents to [eliminate smoking in public housing units|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/081018_Clean_Air_Columbia.pdf].\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Analyzing Community Problems, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/assessment/assessing-community-needs-and-resources/analyzing-community-problems/main]\r\n[Defining and Analyzing the Problem, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/analyze/analyze-community-problems-and-solutions/define-analyze-problem/main]\r\n[Involving People Most Affected by the Problem, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/participation/encouraging-involvement/involve-those-affected/main]\r\n[Identifying Targets and Agents of Change: Who Can Benefit and Who Can Help, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/analyze/where-to-start/identify-targets-and-agents-of-change/main]\r\n','Community Partnership Development intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('COMMUNITY','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','Communicable disease control and prevention depends on an effective network of community partners. Public health agencies receive early warnings of disease outbreaks based on absenteeism reports from school and large employers. They depend on pharmacies to report a spike in over-the-counter medication sales to indicate community spread of disease. They also rely on partners to help share information about disease control and prevention.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nCommunity partners have played a more significant role than ever in public education and disease control through the COVID pandemic. Businesses responded to public health requests to close, implement social distancing strategies, and require face masks in an effort to slow community transmission of COVID-19. Strong partnerships in rural [Saline County|https://www.commonwellalliance.org/news-center/commonwell-blog/lessons-learned-from-rural-community-hospital-on-slowing-the-covid19-curve/] helped the community navigate the pandemic in early 2020, despite recording the highest number of cases per capita in the state of Missouri during the first wave of the pandemic.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Infectious Disease Guiding Principles, ASTHO|https://www.astho.org/Policy-and-Position-Statements/Policy-Statement-on-Infectious-Disease/]\r\n[Public Health and Faith Community Partnerships: Model Practices to Increase Influenza Prevention Among Hard-to-Reach Populations, ASTHO|https://www.astho.org/Infectious-Disease/Public-Health-and-Faith-Community-Partnerships-Model-Practices-to-Increase-Influenza-Prevention-Among-Hard-to-Reach-Populations/]\r\n','Community Partnership Development intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('COMMUNITY','ENVIRONMENT','Although rural and urban Missourians experience the environment in different ways and to varying degrees, the environment in which we live directly impacts our health. Partner organizations and community members should work collaboratively with public health to move environmental public health data into actions that reduce exposure, decrease health risks, and allow all of us to live our healthiest lives.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\n[Kansas City Health Department|https://healthequityguide.org/case-studies/kansas-city-develops-mou-and-shares-space-with-community-organizers/] works collaboratively with the faith-based advocacy group Communities Creating Opportunity to address social determinants of health like unemployment, violence, homelessness, and health inequities.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Partnership for Environmental Public Health, National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/creating-and-maintaining-coalitions-and-partnerships]\r\n','Community Partnership Development intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('COMMUNITY','INJURY','In the last 100 years, public health has increased our life expectancy by 25 years with interventions like immunizations, water fluoridation, infectious disease control, family planning, reducing heart disease and stroke, recognizing tobacco as a health hazard, and seat belt and car seat use. Preventing injuries requires public health agencies to work with partners to identify trends, move upstream to discover causes, and then implement policies and programs that reduce risk and prevent injuries.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nWright County Health Department collaborates with [MODOT|https://www.modot.org/node/13829] and other regional partners to increase seat belt and car seat use in order to prevent child deaths in motor vehicle accidents.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Partnering with Residents, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/learning-guides/partnering-with-residents#/]\r\n','Community Partnership Development intersect with Injury Prevention'),('COMMUNITY','LINKAGE','Strategic collaborative partnerships create a stronger referral system that links all of us to the programs and services we need to live a healthier life and reach our full potential. As chief health strategists, public health leaders play a key role, convening partners, engaging community members, and building trust.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Tips for Engaging Businesses as Public Health Partners, JPHMP|https://journals.lww.com/jphmp/fulltext/2019/09000/tips_for_engaging_local_businesses_as_public.16.aspx]\r\n[Partner Center, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/partner-center]\r\n[Creating and Maintaining Coalitions and Partnerships, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/creating-and-maintaining-coalitions-and-partnerships]','Community Partnership Development intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('COMMUNITY','MATERNAL','The saying, \"It takes a village to raise a child\" is certainly based on truth. Strong partnerships are vital to growing healthy children in thriving families, from conception through their lifetime. Women\'s health also depends on a strong network of partners to provide resources, programs, and services throughout the lifecourse.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\n[Nurses for Newborns|https://www.nursesfornewborns.org/] provides in home visits by registered nurses to assure infants have the opportunity to thrive. The program provides care at no cost to infants with medical conditions, those born to teens or mothers with a disability or mental health concern, and infants in homes with no resources to provide them with basic care. \r\nButler County Health Department partners with Missouri Family Health Council to deliver information about and access to quality contraceptive services through their program [The Right Time|https://mfhc.org/programs-services/the-right-time.html].\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Family Health Resources, National Parent Teacher Association|https://www.pta.org/home/family-resources/health]\r\n[Missouri Family Health Council|https://mfhc.org/for-patients/]\r\n[Advocates for Family Health Program, Legal Services of Eastern Missouri|https://lsem.org/advocates-for-family-health-program/]\r\n[Crisis Counseling, Show Me Hope|https://www.moshowmehope.org/]','Community Partnership Development intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('EMERGENCY','CHRONIC','In order to prevent an increase in illness, complications, and death, it is important that people managing chronic diseases continue routine medical care and disease management practices, even during a public health emergency. Public health agencies should work with clients to support the use of telemedicine, virtual communication platforms, and digital apps to continue self-management of chronic conditions. In addition, prevention efforts may need to be accelerated to counter the disruption of healthy eating patterns, physical activity, routine health visits, and stress management, which may lead to [new chronic disease diagnoses|https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMc2018688], complications, and more serious outcomes.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nIn 2020, [COVID-19 adversely affected people with chronic health conditions|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7308780/] like diabetes, high blood pressure, and COPD. Physicians transitioned to providing routine care through virtual communication and reported that the mental health of their patients worsened during the pandemic.\r\nWhen Hurricane Katrina struck the Gulf Coast in 2005, [people with diabetes|https://care.diabetesjournals.org/content/29/1/158.long] were left in evacuation centers and shelters with little or no control over their eating schedules, available foods, or insulin management.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Emergency Preparedness for People with Chronic Disease, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/resources/infographic/emergency.htm]\r\n[Disaster Planning: People with Chronic Disease, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/features/disaster-planning-chronic-disease/index.html]\r\n[Emergency Planning to Address Chronic Health Conditions in Missouri, MoDHSS, 2006|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/chronic/chronicdisease/EmergencyPlanningReport.pdf]\r\n[Emergency and disaster preparedness for chronically ill patients: a review of recommendations, Tomio, J. and Sato, H., 2014|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4753992/]\r\n[Insuring continuity of care for chronic disease patients after a disaster: key preparedness elements, American Journal of Medical Science, 2008|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2699450/]\r\n[Prescription Medication Preparedness Initiative, 2015|https://www.phe.gov/about/OPP/dhsp/Documents/pmpi-mtg.pdf]\r\n[My Diabetes Emergency Plan - An Important Checklist for People with Diabetes|http://www.mydiabetesemergencyplan.com/]\r\n[Patient Preparedness Plan, Diabetes Disaster Response Coalition|http://main.diabetes.org/dorg/PDFs/emergency-preparedness/DDRCPatientPreparednessPlan2018Short.pdf]\r\n[Tips for Emergency Preparedness, American Diabetes Association|https://www.diabetes.org/resources/disaster-relief/tips-for-emergency-preparedness]\r\n[COVID-19 Resources, Diabetes Disaster Response Coalition|https://www.diabetesdisasterresponse.org/covid-resources]\r\n[Community Assessment for Public Health Emergency Response (CASPER), CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/casper/]\r\n[Rx Open & Rx on the Run, Healthcare Ready|https://healthcareready.org/about/]\r\n[Living with Diabetes: Be Prepared!, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/diabetes/managing/preparedness.html]\r\n\r\n\r\n','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('EMERGENCY','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','Communicable disease outbreaks are the most common type of public health emergency - a Hepatitis A outbreak, a rabies exposure, a novel virus, or a flu season where the vaccine is not a good match to the circulating strain of virus. Most often these outbreaks are limited in scope, and an effective investigation and contact tracing push, coupled with proven interventions like isolation, quarantine, and vaccination can quickly stop the spread of disease.\r\nIn 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic severely tested public health\'s capacity to respond to a large-scale communicable disease emergency. [Inadequate testing resources, delayed test results|https://www.heart.org/en/news/2020/04/02/covid-19-science-why-testing-is-so-important], mixed messages, and public angst made efficient investigation and contact tracing virtually impossible. [Recommendations for isolation, quarantine, and other non-pharmaceutical interventions|https://www.contagionlive.com/news/public-health-perspective-covid19-lessons-and-challenges] were politicized, criticized, and ignored by many people, allowing the virus to spread  rapidly through communities and dramatically increasing the workload for communicable disease professionals.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nBetween 2017 and 2020, nearly [700 cases of Hepatitis A|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/communicable/hepatitisa/index.php#outbreak] were linked to an ongoing outbreak across Missouri. The cases were not caused by a common source of food, beverage, or drugs. The virus appeared to be spread through direct person-to-person contact.\r\nIn 2016 a [puppy in Howell County tested positive for rabies|https://www.ky3.com/content/news/rabies-west-plains-378456291.html]. The health department investigation led to 8 dogs being euthanized, and 32 people being treated with post-exposure rabies vaccination.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Ensuring Equity in COVID-19 Planning, Response, and Recovery Decision-Making, Human Impact Partners|https://humanimpact.org/hipprojects/ensuring-equity-in-covid-19-planning-response-and-recovery-decision-making/] [Community Assessment for Public Health Emergency Response (CASPER), CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/casper/default.htm]\r\n[Infectious Disease Emergency Response Plan, San Francisco Dept of Public Health|https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/sites/default/files/public/downloads/practice/entire_ider_plan.pdf]\r\n[Health Sector Resilience Checklist for HighConsequence Infectious DiseasesâInformed by\r\nthe Domestic US Ebola Response, Johns Hopkins|https://www.centerforhealthsecurity.org/our-work/pubs_archive/pubs-pdfs/2017/HCID_Final_Report_05.23.2017.pdf] (see Recommendations and Checklist pg 40 - 48)','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Communicable Disease Investigation'),('EMERGENCY','ENVIRONMENT','Public health has an important role in emergency preparedness and response to environmental public health issues. In its [Environmental Health Emergency Response Guide|https://www.cdc.gov/NCEH/ehs/Docs/EH_Emergency_Response_Guide.pdf], the CDC says during an emergency the primary role of environmental public health specialists is \"to provide services essential for protecting and ensuring the well-being of the people in affected areas, with an emphasis on prevention and control of communicable diseases and exposures to hazardous materials.\"\r\nHistorically, public health agencies have collected and tested dead birds for the presence of West Nile Virus, assured food and water quality after a disaster, worked with epidemiologists to investigate foodborne or waterborne disease outbreaks, ensured sanitation in emergency shelters, and evaluated air quality.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\nAfter the 2011 tornado in Joplin, environmental public health specialists worked closely with epidemiologists and the CDC to investigate the cause of 13 cases of [unusual wound infection|https://blogs.cdc.gov/publichealthmatters/2011/08/tornado/]. The cause was determined to be a rare infection caused by fungi found in soil and decaying wood, leading to a [new recommendation for early treatment|https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6029a5.htm] for suspected infections among people injured in a tornado.\r\nIn 2007 environmental public health specialists collected dead birds to test for West Nile Virus in order to better understand the prevalence of the virus in the bird population.\r\nIn response to Zika, between 2016 - 2019, environmental public health specialists in Springfield partnered with Missouri State University to [trap and test 35,000 mosquitos|https://www.ky3.com/content/news/MSU-Department-of-Public-Health-identifies-mosquitoes-488974121.html] in an effort to estimate the number of disease-carrying mosquitos and prevent future outbreaks. \r\nSt. Charles County Health Department has [worked proactively to reduce the number of disease-carrying mosquitoes|https://www.youtube.com/watch?reload=9&time_continue=65&v=pRafCKnLkXk&feature=emb_logo] by spraying, treating stagnant water, and encouraging community members to eliminate standing water and mosquito habitat.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Environmental Health Playbook: Emergency Preparedness, APHA|https://apha.org/-/media/files/pdf/topics/environment/playbook_emergency_preparedness.ashx?la=en&hash=969F87B7711C236895C8A9034B761B68E2BBA9FC]\r\n[Environmental Health Emergency Response Guide, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/NCEH/ehs/Docs/EH_Emergency_Response_Guide.pdf]\r\n[Emergency and Terrorism Preparedness for\r\nEnvironmental Health Practitioners, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/etp/default.htm]\r\n[Environmental Health in Emergencies, WHO|http://www.who.int/environmental_health_emergencies/en/]\r\n[Environmental Health in Emergencies: Prevention, WHO|http://www.who.int/environmental_health_emergencies/prevention/en/]\r\n[Comprehensive Disaster Assessment and Readiness Tools, ATSDR|https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/CDART.html]\r\n\r\nTraining:\r\n[Environmental Health Training in Emergency Response, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/elearn/ehter.htm]\r\n[Environmental Assessment Training, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/elearn/eats/index.html]\r\n','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('EMERGENCY','INJURY','The [risk of injury|https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/illness-injury.html] increases during an emergency. [Flood waters|https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/floods/floodsafety.html] can hide debris. Structural damage to buildings can create an increased risk for fire or collapse. [High heat|https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/extremeheat/index.html] can cause life threatening heat-related illness. Medical treatment for injuries may be delayed, leading to a higher risk of infection. Public health agencies are tasked with identifying potential public health, health care, mental/behavioral\r\nhealth, and environmental health hazards, vulnerabilities, and risks as part of emergency preparedness. They should also assess and work to mitigate the impact of an interruption in public health, health care, human services, mental/behavioral health, and environmental health services and supporting infrastructure because of an emergency.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nAfter the 2011 tornado in Joplin, local public health professionals worked closely with the CDC to investigate the cause of 13 cases of [unusual wound infection|https://blogs.cdc.gov/publichealthmatters/2011/08/tornado/]. The cause was determined to be a rare infection caused by fungi found in soil and decaying wood, leading to a [new recommendation for early treatment|https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6029a5.htm] for suspected infections among people injured in a tornado.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Health and Safety Concerns for All Disasters, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/alldisasters.html]\r\n[Prevent Illness and Injury After a Disaster, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/disasters/illness-injury.html]\r\n[Prepare for Your Health, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/prepyourhealth/takeaction/index.htm]\r\n','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Injury Prevention'),('EMERGENCY','LINKAGE','Emergency response calls for accelerated levels of partnership and resource sharing. The priority response to any emergency is life safety, followed by assuring emergency human services. These may include providing food and shelter, relief supplies, health care, mental health care, disease prevention, and other resources specific to the needs created by the emergency. Coordination can be a challenging task, requiring collaboration and an efficient referral system.\r\nIn Missouri, associations like the Governorâs Faith-Based and Community Service Partnership for Disaster Recovery (The Partnership) and the Missouri Voluntary Organizations Active in Disaster (MO VOAD) support an integrated system of coordination. At the local level, public health agencies collaborate with partners through Community Organizations Active in Disaster (COAD) to coordinate emergency human services.\r\n\r\nCase Studies:\r\n[Three communities blend short and long-term [housing|https://youtu.be/iY80SjnF1Gc] needs with limited resources to keep residents in their community after the Joplin tornado.\r\nOzark Center leads a community collaboration effort to provide [emotional first aid and crisis counseling|http://joplinproud.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Vicki-Mieseler-Ozark-Center-Presentation.pdf] to Joplin residents following the 2011 Joplin tornado.\r\n[St. Charles County COAD|http://www.communitycouncilstc.org/disasteremergency-planning-coad] helps community members find information and resources to prepare for, recover from, and rebuild after a disaster.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Missouri COAD Manual, SEMA|https://sema.dps.mo.gov/programs/documents/mo-coad-manual.pdf]\r\n[The Partnership, SEMA|https://sema.dps.mo.gov/programs/thepartnership.php]\r\n[Missouri Volunteers Active in Disaster, MO VOAD|https://movoad.communityos.org/cms/resources]\r\n','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('EMERGENCY','MATERNAL','Public health emergencies can have a direct or indirect impact on families. Public health agencies must consider how mothers, children and families may be impacted by a public health emergency. They may be primarily affected by illness, injury or death. But they may also face secondary affects from loss of employment, homelessness, hunger, trauma, stress, or separation. Public health planning should include a focus on equipping families to prepare for, withstand and recover from public health emergencies. It should also work with community partners to create strategies to mitigate the impact of public health emergencies on mothers, children and families and support their recovery.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nAs the COVID pandemic was just getting started in Missouri in March 2020, Missouri Budget Project released a [white paper|https://www.mobudget.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/MO_COVID_March2020.pdf] describing the projected impact on families. The full impact of COVID-19 on families will likely last decades and may never be fully quantified.\r\nThe first case of [Zika virus|https://www.cdc.gov/zika/pregnancy/index.html] was [reported in Brazil in 2015|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5800195/]. Scientists discovered the virus was being carried by infected mosquitos and could also be spread through sexual intercourse with an infected person, even one who was asymptomatic. In many cases the virus was passed from pregnant mother to her unborn child, causing a birth defect called microcephaly and other severe fetal brain defects.\r\n \r\nResources:\r\n[Disaster Safety for Expecting and New Parents, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/features/disaster-planning-parents/index.html]\r\n[Reproductive Health in Emergency Preparedness and Response, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/emergency/index.html]\r\n[Preparedness, Response, and Recovery Considerations for Children and Families: Workshop Summary|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK195865/]\r\n[Early Childhood Disaster-Related Resources for Policy Makers, US DHHS|https://www.acf.hhs.gov/ohsepr/policy-makers]\r\n[Family Disaster Preparedness, FEMA|https://www.ready.gov/]\r\n[Reproductive Health: Emergency Response Activities for Infectious Diseases, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/emergency/emergency-response-infectious-disease.html]\r\n[Reproductive Health: Emergency Preparedness and Response Training Course, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/emergency/training-course/index.html]','Emergency Preparedness and Response intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('INNER','CHRONIC','Chronic diseases are conditions that last for a long time and generally canât be prevented by vaccines or cured by medicine. Chronic diseases usually require ongoing medical attention and may limit daily activities. Examples are diabetes, arthritis, cancer, heart and lung disease, asthma, and obesity. Almost 9 in 10 Americans over age 65 have at least one chronic health condition. Public health agencies work with partners to share information, develop policies, and create environments that support activities to prevent chronic disease â activities like smoking cessation, healthy eating, and exercising.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_806c9aba46c14f3288907fce94d96555~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education on chronic disease, including mental illness, and chemical dependency\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local chronic disease prevention and management community partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement a prioritized chronic disease prevention plan\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for chronic disease prevention and management policies and initiatives\r\n - Support community?based prevention and management of chronic disease\r\n - Lead community efforts to reduce rates of tobacco use, reduce youth initiation, increase cessation, and reduce exposure to second-hand smoke\r\n - Lead community efforts to increase rates of healthy eating and active living that utilize best practices that are aligned with national and state guidelines\r\n - Coordinate and integrate other categorically funded communicable disease control programs and services\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_ebe19f9d7cc44f5fb32a86e9610078b8.pdf] \r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[The State of Obesity: Better policies for a healthier America. 2023. Trust for America\'s Health|https://www.tfah.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/TFAH-2023-ObesityReport-FINAL.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font>\r\n[Chronic Disease Prevention and Management, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/chronic/chronicdisease/index.html]\r\n[List of Chronic Diseases, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/chronic/]\r\n[Chronic Disease Indicators by State and Indicator, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/cdi/index.html]\r\n[Chronic Disease Toolkit, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/chronic/toolkit.php]\r\n[Chronic Disease Prevention Messaging Toolkit, NPHIC|https://www.nphic.org/toolkits/chronicdisease]\r\n[Chronic Disease Prevention Toolkit, NACCHO|https://toolbox.naccho.org/pages/tool-view.html?id=2322]\r\n','Chronic Disease Prevention'),('INNER','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','Public health agencies work with partners to slow and stop the spread of disease in a community. These communicable disease control strategies include using surveillance to quickly identify diseases that pose a threat to public health, isolate their cause, and prevent their spread using a variety of methods. Immunizations, community education, and non-pharmaceutical interventions like social distancing play a significant role in communicable disease control. Public health agencies respond to data showing a disparate impact of communicable disease and work to assure health equity.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_15d921ca5e9440f7b131667891f301ed~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant information on communicable diseases and their control\r\n - Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant information on strategies to increase local immunization rates\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local communicable disease control community partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement a communicable disease control plan prioritizing important ?communicable diseases\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for communicable disease control policies and initiatives\r\n - Support community?based initiatives for the prevention of communicable disease spread\r\n - Receive public health laboratory and clinical reports for reference and confirmatory testing related to communicable diseases\r\n - Identify and respond to communicable disease outbreaks in accordance with national, state, and local mandates and guidelines\r\n - Assure notification for partners of newly diagnosed cases of reportable diseases in accordance with national, state, and local mandates and guidelines\r\n - Assure the appropriate treatment of individuals with active tuberculosis, including the provision of directly observed therapy in accordance with national, state, and local mandates and guidelines\r\n - Exercise quarantine authority in accordance with national, state, and local mandates and guidelines\r\n - Conduct disease investigations, including contact tracing and notification\r\n - Facilitate enforcement of emergency health orders via statutory authority (community ?disease containment, mandated treatment, boil water orders, etc.)\r\n - Support local screening/testing of reportable diseases\r\n - Assure access to STD and HIV testing\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_f7a4f427160c4b4fb78e05b01e1f35f7.pdf] \r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Communicable Disease Resources, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/communicable/]\r\n[Communicable Disease Investigation Reference Manual (C-DIRM), MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/healthcondiseases/communicable/communicabledisease/cdmanual/index.php]\r\n[Immunization and Infectious Diseases, Healthy People 2020|https://www.healthypeople.gov/2020/topics-objectives/topic/immunization-and-infectious-diseases]\r\n[National Foundation for Infectious Diseases|https://www.nfid.org/infectious-diseases/]\r\n[Infectious Disease Toolkit for Continuums of Care (People Who are Homeless), HUD|https://files.hudexchange.info/resources/documents/Infectious-Disease-Toolkit-for-CoCs-Preventing-and-Managing-the-Spread-of-Infectious-Disease-for-People-Experiencing-Homelessness.pdf]\r\n[COVID-19 and Equity, APHA|https://apha.org/topics-and-issues/communicable-disease/coronavirus/equity]','Communicable Disease Control'),('INNER','ENVIRONMENT','According to the American Public Health Association, \"Environmental health is the branch of public health that focuses on the relationships between people and their environment; promotes human health and well-being; and fosters healthy and safe communities. Environmental health is a key part of any comprehensive public health system. The field works to advance policies and programs to reduce chemical and other environmental exposures in air, water, soil and food to protect people and provide communities with healthier environments.â\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_d189b1978b6d453789a8fadaff51bf8d~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant information on environmental public health issues and health impacts from both common and toxic exposure sources\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local environmental public health community partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement an environmental public health plan to prevent and reduce exposures to health hazards in the environment\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for environmental public health policies and initiatives\r\n - Support community-based environmental public health\r\n - Conduct mandated environmental public health laboratory testing to protect food, drinking water, recreational water use, and liquid and solid waste streams in accordance with federal, state, and local laws and regulations\r\n - Conduct mandated environmental public health inspections (including within school, child care, and correctional facilities) to protect food, drinking water, recreational water use, and liquid and solid waste streams in accordance with federal, state, and local laws and regulations\r\n - Protect the population from hazardous chemical exposure in accordance with federal, state, and local laws and regulations\r\n - Protect the population from unnecessary radiation exposure in accordance with federal, state, and local laws and regulations\r\n - Participate in broad land use planning and sustainable development (e.g., consideration of housing, urban development, recreational facilities, and transportation)\r\n - Coordinate and integrate other categorically funded communicable disease control programs and services\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_8f63ffc35c3a4a6f8254892a3f8dba63.pdf]  \r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Missouri Environmental Health Association|https://mehamo.org/]\r\n[Environmental Public Health Performance Standards, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nceh/ehs/envphps/]\r\n[Building Understanding of Environmental Health:  A Communications Toolkit, Frameworks Institute|http://frameworksinstitute.org/toolkits/environmentalhealth/]\r\n[Environmental Health Playbook:  Investing in a Robust Environmental Health System, NEPHC|https://www.apha.org/-/media/files/pdf/topics/environment/eh_playbook.ashx?la=en&hash=FBAE72B837D58A3C3145602B1043250DE7BD41BD]\r\n[The Value of Environmental Health Services (2016), NEHPC|\r\nhttps://www.apha.org/-/media/files/pdf/topics/environment/eh_values.ashx?la=en&hash=6F6BE07BDA09712818CF5489941CF8169B2598ED]\r\n[Environment, Health, You (video), APHA|https://vimeo.com/32226544]','Environmental Public Health'),('INNER','INJURY','Most injuries are preventable. Public health agencies work with partners through four steps to identify the causes and prevent injuries. Agencies start by using data to define which injuries are occurring and to whom. They look at trends â how injuries are changing over time â and what impact injury prevention programs are having. Secondly, agencies try to understand why injuries are occurring â what factors are putting people at risk for injury. Thirdly, public health agencies and their partners develop and test prevention strategies and programs. They study how well the programs work to prevent additional injuries, and make adjustments as needed. Finally, agencies apply what theyâve learned to preventing other types of injuries, and share best practices with other communities.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_e1ebe80cee904241b562a27a08a4254a~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education on injury prevention and control\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local injury prevention community partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement a prioritized injury prevention plan\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for injury prevention policies and initiatives\r\n - Support community?based injury prevention initiatives\r\n - Work with partners to implement evidence?based and population?based interventions that mitigate suicide risk\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_8ce607953a494c369fcfc6b3d9ca8cf9.pdf] \r\n\r\nAdditional Resource:\r\n[Fatal Injury Data Visualization Tool, CDC|https://wisqars.cdc.gov/data/explore-data/home]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Injury and Violence Prevention, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/families/injuries/index.php]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Injury Prevention and Control, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/injury/]\r\n[Safe Kids, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/families/injuries/safekids.php]\r\n[Web-Based Injury Statistics Query and Reporting Systems (WISQARS), CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/injury/wisqars/index.html]\r\n[Supervisor Toolkit: Injury Prevention, UCDavis|https://safetyservices.ucdavis.edu/units/ehs/workplace-safety-industrial-hygiene/injury-prevention/supervisor-toolkit]\r\n[Injury Prevention Outreach Program, MU Health|https://www.muhealth.org/conditions-treatments/emergency/trauma/injury-prevention]','Injury Prevention'),('INNER','LINKAGE','Public health agencies donât have the resources to physically provide all the programs and services needed in a community. They depend on a strong network of partners, each with specific areas of expertise. When public health and its partners work together, they build a strong foundation for well-being that ensures every member of the community has access to the programs and services they need to reach their full potential and live healthier lives. \r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_39b703f2464d40fba1492b9ff31e060e~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education to the health care system in the LPHAâs jurisdiction\r\n - Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education to the community on the health care system\r\n - Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education to the community on the behavioral health care system\r\n - Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant education to the community on community resources available in the LPHAâs region\r\n - Conduct inspection and licensing of health care facilities to improve patient safety\r\n - Improve patient safety through licensing, monitoring, and discipline of health care providers\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local medical and behavioral healthcare community partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement a prioritized plan for increasing access to quality health care\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for policies and initiatives that increase access to quality medical and behavioral healthcare\r\n - Support community-based initiatives that increase access to quality medical and behavioral healthcare\r\n - Assure access to patient-centered medical home care and quality care\r\n - Utilize public health staff as facilitators of clinical and community linkages\r\n - Procure, maintain, manage, and distribute biological and therapeutic products to health care providers\r\n - Assure access to STD and HIV treatment\r\n - Provide certified birth and death certificates\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_e98639c4e6864292abe5ba9396e6e98f.pdf] \r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Hospital Community Linkages, BHNSTL|https://www.bhnstl.org/home/hcl/]\r\n[Clinical-Community Linkages, AHRQ|https://www.ahrq.gov/ncepcr/tools/community/index.html]\r\n[Clinical-Community Relationships Measures (CCRM) Atlas, AHRQ|https://www.ahrq.gov/prevention/resources/chronic-care/clinical-community-relationships-measures-atlas/index.html]\r\n[Clinical-Community Evaluation Roadmap, AHRQ|https://www.ahrq.gov/prevention/resources/chronic-care/clinical-community-relationships-eval-roadmap/index.html]\r\n[Community Linkages for the Prevention and Control of Chronic Diseases, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/dhdsp/pubs/docs/ccl-practitioners-guide.pdf]\r\n[Integrating Services for Community Health, SOPHE|https://www.sophe.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/National-WIC-Association_final2.pdf]\r\n[Strengthening Community-Clinical Linkages, ASTHO|https://www.astho.org/Programs/Clinical-to-Community-Connections/Cross-Sector-Partnerships-to-Address-Social-Determinants-of-Health/Strengthening-Community-Clinical-Linkages_Meeting-Summary/]','Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('INNER','MATERNAL','Healthy People 2030 says improving the well-being of mothers, infants, and children is an important public health goal. Their well-being determines the health of the next generation and can help predict future public health challenges for families, communities, and the health care system. This foundational area of public health expertise includes addressing conditions that affect health behaviors and improving wellness indicators for women, children, and families.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_00bf5ff0f49a485e8cb81b82c617bf8b~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant information on emerging and ongoing maternal, child, and family health trends\r\n - Provide timely, accurate, and locally relevant information on the consequences of Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs)\r\n - Identify statewide, regional, and local maternal, child, and family health partners and their capacities\r\n - Develop and implement a prioritized maternal, child, and family health prevention plan, using life course expertise and an understanding of health disparities\r\n - Advocate and seek funding for maternal, child, and family health policies and initiatives\r\n - Support community-based maternal, child, and family health initiatives\r\n - Identify, disseminate, and promote emerging and evidence-based information about early interventions in the prenatal and early childhood period that optimize positive social-emotional development and lifelong health\r\n - Identify, disseminate, and promote emerging and evidence-based information about early interventions in the prenatal period to reduce infant mortality and pre-term birth outcomes\r\n - Assure mandated newborn screenings are performed in order to detect and prevent the developmental impairments and life-threatening illnesses associated with congenital disorders specified for Missouri\r\n - Assure access to maternal and infant services (e.g., maternity support, WIC)\r\n - Assure adequate pre-natal care\r\n - Assure family planning services\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_83dff250d5be4c3abdf9436a1a5fab1e.pdf] \r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Public Health\'s Role in Mental Health Promotion and Suicide Prevention (2023), ASTHO, CDC, CLASP, MHA|https://www.astho.org/topic/report/public-healths-role-in-mental-health-promotion-and-suicide-prevention/]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font>\r\n[Maternal, Child Health Block Grant, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/families/mch-block-grant/]\r\n[Maternal, Infant, and Child Health, Healthy People 2020, CDC|https://www.healthypeople.gov/2020/topics-objectives/topic/maternal-infant-and-child-health]\r\n[Family-focused Public Health:  Supporting Homes and Families in Policy and Practice (2019), NIH|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6435478/]\r\n[Family Health, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/family/]\r\n[Missouri AIM Severe Hypertension Pregnancy Toolkit, Missouri Hospital Association|https://www.mhanet.com/mhaimages/sqi/maternal_Health/MOAIM_MM.pdf]\r\n[State Infant Mortality Toolkit, AMCHP|http://www.amchp.org/programsandtopics/data-assessment/InfantMortalityToolkit/Pages/default.aspx]\r\n[MCH Needs Assessment Toolkit, National MCH Workforce Development Center|https://www.mchneeds.net/]','Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('MISC','HELP','Learn more about Missouri\'s Foundational Public Health Services model and begin using it to transform your public health agency.\r\n[FPHS Model Overview (YouTube video)|https://youtu.be/rxKjI9gHdMQ]\r\n[FPHS Model Overview (pdf)|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/FPHS/FPHS_overview_Full.pdf]\r\n[FPHS Model Development Process|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/FPHS/FPHS_Development_Process.pdf]\r\n[FPHS Model Discussion Tool|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Gearbox/Gearbox_Overview.pdf]\r\n[FPHS Model Resources|https://healthiermo.org/fphs.html] \r\n\r\nFor help with the academic version of Missouri\'s FPHS model, contact #HealthierMO\'s Communication Coordinator Jaci McReynolds at [jmcreynolds@healthiermo.org|mailto:jmcreynolds@healthiermo.org].','Click here for help '),('MISC','INNER_RING','Although Health Equity and Social Determinants of Health are called out as a separate component in Missouriâs Foundational Public Health Services model, in practice they are integrated into all public health capabilities and areas of expertise. \r\nPublic health agencies must have the ability to work with their partners to address health inequities and social determinants of health in order to create an environment and policies that support conditions for optimal health for all people. \r\nPublic health agencies should be able to analyze data to identify health inequities, make health equity a strategic priority, and apply evidence-based strategies and interventions to restore health equity in every Missouri community.\r\n\r\nCore Competencies:\r\n - Describe the concept of diversity as it applies to individuals and populations.\r\n - Describe the diversity of individuals and populations in a community.\r\n - Describe the ways diversity influences policies, programs, services, and the health of a community.\r\n - Recognize, support, and incorporate diverse perspectives in developing, implementing, and evaluating policies, programs, and services that affect the health of a community.\r\n - Address, ensure, and advocate for the diversity of individuals and populations being addressed in policies, programs, and services that affect the health of a community.\r\n - Describe, address, and evaluate the effects of policies, programs, and services on different populations in a community.\r\n - Describe and demonstrate the value of a diverse public health workforce.\r\n - Advocate for and take measures to support a diverse public health workforce.\r\n\r\n[Take Action: Resource for Improvement|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Gearbox/Gearbox_Equity_SDOH.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Structural Determinants of Health Differences from Social Determinants of Health, UCLA BRITE Center for Science|https://ncvhs.hhs.gov/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/Presentation-Panel-4-UCLA-Vickie-Mays-508.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Becoming Better Messengers, The Network for Public Health Law|https://www.networkforphl.org/resources/topics/trainings/becoming-better-messengers/]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Five Recommendations for How Implementation Science Can Better Advance Equity, Academy Health, 2019|https://academyhealth.org/blog/2019-04/five-recommendations-how-implementation-science-can-better-advance-equity]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Undoing the Drivers of Health Inequity, Change Lab Solutions|https://www.changelabsolutions.org/drivers-health-inequity]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Racial Equity Toolkit, Collective Impact, 2023|https://collectiveimpactforum.org/resource/racial-equity-toolkit/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_medium=email&utm_content=Racial%20Equity%20Toolkit%20&utm_campaign=CIF20230711KeynotePod]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Racial Justice Competencies for Public Health Professionals (model and toolkit), PHTCN and NNPHI|https://rjcmph.org/]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Cultural Competency and Language Access Resource Guides, US Office of Minority Health|https://www.minorityhealth.hhs.gov/omh/Content.aspx?ID=18516&lvl=2&lvlid=19&utm_campaign=health_equity_link&utm_medium=email&utm_source=govdelivery]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Health Equity Tracker (state and county level data)|https://healthequitytracker.org/]\r\n[HOPE Initiative (state level data)|https://www.hopeinitiative.org/]\r\n[Health Equity Zones Toolkit, Rhode Island|https://health.ri.gov/publications/toolkits/health-equity-zones.pdf]\r\n[Health Equity Measures, Rhode Island|https://health.ri.gov/publications/factsheets/HealthEquityIndicators.pdf]\r\n[An Equity Lens Tool for Health Departments, Human Impact Partners|https://static1.squarespace.com/static/534b4cdde4b095a3fb0cae21/t/5fce6f8ffb43de2fe9ce4c29/1607364496160/HIP-BCHC-Health-Equity-Lens-Tool-12-2020+%282%29.pdf]\r\n[Introduction to Equity, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/learning-guides/introduction-to-equity#/]\r\n[Identifying and Understanding Health Inequities, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpao/state-local-programs/health-equity-guide/pdf/health-equity-guide/Health-Equity-Guide-sect-1-4.pdf]\r\n[Health Equity and Social Determinants of Health, ASTHO|https://www.astho.org/Programs/Health-Equity/]\r\n[Understand and Identify Root Causes of Inequities, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/learning-guides/understand-and-identify-root-causes-of-inequities#/]\r\n[Develop Strategies to Promote Health and Equity, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/learning-guides/develop-strategies-to-promote-health-and-equity#/]\r\n[Guidelines for Achieving Health Equity in Public Health Practice (2009), NACCHO|https://www.health.state.mn.us/communities/practice/resources/equitylibrary/docs/Guidelines_for_Achieving_Health_Equity_in_Public_Health_Practice_1.pdf]\r\n[Building Organizational Capacity to Advance Health Equity, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dnpao/state-local-programs/health-equity-guide/pdf/health-equity-guide/Health-Equity-Guide-sect-1-1.pdf]\r\n[Moving to Institutional Equity, National Association of Chronic Disease Directors|https://cdn.ymaws.com/www.chronicdisease.org/resource/resmgr/Gillan\'s_files/Health_Equity_June_2017.pdf]\r\n[Communities in Action: Pathways to Health Equity (2017), NASEM|http://nationalacademies.org/hmd/reports/2017/communities-in-action-pathways-to-health-equity.aspx]\r\n[Tools for Putting SDOH into Action, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/socialdeterminants/tools/index.htm]\r\n[The EveryONE Project Toolkit, AAFP|https://www.aafp.org/patient-care/social-determinants-of-health/everyone-project/eop-tools.html]\r\n[Promoting Health Equity, CDC Resource|https://www.cdc.gov/nccdphp/dch/programs/healthycommunitiesprogram/tools/pdf/SDOH-workbook.pdf]\r\n[SDOH for Rural Health Toolkit|https://www.ruralhealthinfo.org/toolkits/sdoh]\r\n[Systems Change and Deep Equity, Change Elemental|https://changeelemental.org/resources/systems-change-and-deep-equity-monograph/]\r\n[Race Equity and Inclusion Action Guide, Annie E Casey Foundation|https://www.aecf.org/m/resourcedoc/AECF_EmbracingEquity7Steps-2014.pdf]\r\n[Ensuring Equity in COVID-19 Planning, Response, and Recovery Decision-Making, Human Impact Partners|https://humanimpact.org/hipprojects/ensuring-equity-in-covid-19-planning-response-and-recovery-decision-making/]\r\n[COVID-19 Vaccine Equity Toolkit, Kaiser Permanente|https://about.kaiserpermanente.org/content/dam/kp/mykp/documents/instructions/covid-19-vaccine-equity-toolkit-external.pdf]\r\n[Health Equity Guiding Principles for Inclusive Communication, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/healthcommunication/HealthEquityGuidingPrinciples.pdf]','Health Equity and Social Determinants of Health'),('MISC','OUTER_RING','In addition to the foundational public health capabilities and areas of expertise, local public health agencies in Missouri offer unique programs and services that meet specific needs in their own communities. Missouri public health agencies have a rich history of creatively solving the challenge of increasing demand for services with shrinking resources. The outer ring on Missouriâs Foundational Public Health Services model reflects local programs and services that may not be fundamental statewide, but are important to meet unique gaps in individual communities.\r\n\r\nMissouri Stories:\r\n[In Home and Home Health Services, Shannon County|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/083019_Shannon_Co_HomeHealth.pdf]\r\n[Fitness Center and Dental Care, Dade County|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/092818_Dade_Fitness_Center.pdf]\r\n[Home Health Services, Johnson and Montgomery Counties|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/102618_Home_Health_Fazzi_MOCO_Johnson.pdf]','Local Programs and Services'),('ORGANIZATION','CHRONIC','Key public health capabilities necessary to move the dial on chronic disease prevention and management includes the capacity to utilize information technology. The COVID pandemic necessitated the use of telecommunications and telemedicine to maintain contact with people with chronic diseases. Public health agencies should increasingly explore the opportunities provided by information technology to improve public health in our communities.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nFourteen local public health agencies in rural southeast Missouri collaborated to implement [electronic health records|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/122118_EHR_Cape.pdf].\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Health IT, Healthy People 2030|https://health.gov/healthypeople/objectives-and-data/browse-objectives/health-it]\r\n[Defining Public Health Informatics, Public Health Informatics Institute|https://www.phii.org/defining-public-health-informatics#:~:text=Public%20Health%20informatics%20is%20the,responsive%20to%20the%20user\'s%20needs.]\r\n','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('ORGANIZATION','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','The 2020 COVID pandemic highlighted the need for public health agencies to have competency in cross-cutting organizational administrative skills such as legal services, leveraging funding, defending budgets, and advocating for the role of public health. Never before has the authority of public health agencies to carry out their responsibility to protect public health been so challenged.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nAt the end of Missouri\'s 2020 legislative session, language was added to an omnibus package that would [strip local public health boards of their authority|https://www.newstribune.com/news/news/story/2020/may/07/late-moving-proposal-could-keep-local-health-departments-making-health-rules/826738/] to make any rules that would prevent the spread of communicable diseases. Sponsoring legislators suggested this authority should be held only by county commissioners, with local public health experts acting only in an advisory capacity.\r\nIn 2019, the Missouri legislature passed [Senate Bill 391|https://trackbill.com/bill/missouri-senate-bill-391-modifies-provisions-relating-to-agricultural-operations/1688870/], which removed local public health agencies\' authority to \"impose standards or requirements on an agricultural operation.\" The change prevented new restrictions on concentrated animal feeding operations (CAFOs) and eliminated existing local regulations, even those that had been in place for nearly 30 years.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Developing a Plan for Increasing Participation in Community Action, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/participation/encouraging-involvement/increase-participation/main]\r\n[Involving People Most Affected by the Problem, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/participation/encouraging-involvement/involve-those-affected/main]\r\n[Involving Key Influentials in the Initiative, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/participation/encouraging-involvement/key-influentials/main] ','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('ORGANIZATION','ENVIRONMENT','In order to deliver foundational public health programs and services, Missouriâs public health agencies must achieve competency in cross-cutting organizational administrative skills and the ability to clearly articulate the reach and value of governmental public health in building healthy communities. Shifts in the culture and environmental changes offer public health agencies the opportunity to address issues that affect the health of entire communities.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nAn increasing groundswell of public attention around climate change provides public health a platform on which to discuss the [impact of climate change|https://www.cdc.gov/climateandhealth/effects/default.htm] on the environment and our health. Extreme temperatures, increased allergens and air pollution, vectorborne disease, water quality, and emerging threats all affect public health.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Preparing for the Regional Health Impacts of Climate Change in the United States, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/climateandhealth/docs/Health_Impacts_Climate_Change-508_final.pdf]\r\n[Guidance and Trainings (on climate change and public health), CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/climateandhealth/guidance.htm]','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('ORGANIZATION','INJURY','In order to deliver foundational public health programs and services, Missouriâs public health agencies must achieve competency in cross-cutting organizational administrative skills, including leadership. Implementing effective policies and programs to prevent injuries requires public health leaders to collect and analyze data, convene partners, and lead strategic planning efforts.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nWith leadership from the Kansas City Health Department, partners in the Kansas City are addressing [violence|https://dashboards.mysidewalk.com/kansas-city-mo-chip-dashboard/violent-crime] as a preventable public health issue.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[National Leadership Academy for the Public\'s Health, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/nlaph/index.html]\r\n[Center for Health Leadership and Practice, Public Health Institute|https://healthleadership.org/]\r\n','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Injury Prevention'),('ORGANIZATION','LINKAGE','When public health professionals clearly understand the distinct, but interrelated roles of primary care and public health, they can lead community partners to work more collaboratively to reduce healthcare costs and improve efficiency of public health and healthcare systems. Public health systems should focus on population health and prevention, while healthcare systems focus on treating illness and restoring health in individuals.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\n[Douglas County Health Department|http://www.dchd.org/] created a unique partnership with local physicians to help with diabetes management. Clinicians referred patients with a new diabetes diagnosis to the public health agency, where they received information, ongoing support from a public health educator, and connection with their peers. This partnership was designed to increase disease management compliance, lower the incidence of complications from diabetes, and reduce healthcare costs overall.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Improving the Effectiveness of Health Care and Public Health: A Multiscale Complex Systems Analysis|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1470498/]','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Linkages to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('ORGANIZATION','MATERNAL','Primary capabilities under the category Organizational Administrative Competencies include the capacity to assure continuous quality improvement, use performance management systems, and develop employees. Missouri\'s Maternal, Child Health program received a much needed boost in this area in 2020 when Saint Louis University formed an academic-practice partnership and created a [Center of Excellence in Maternal and Child Health Education, Science and Practice|https://www.slu.edu/public-health-social-justice/centers_institutes/maternal-child-health-center-of-excellence.php]. The Center will provide maternal and child health students with MCH-focused research, academic, leadership, and practical training.  \r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\n[Engaging Diverse Populations: State Examples, Association of Maternal and Child Health Programs|http://www.amchp.org/programsandtopics/family-engagement/SiteAssets/Pages/default/Engaging%20Diverse%20Populations%20Case%20Study.pdf]\r\n[Family Engagement: State Examples, Association of Maternal and Child Health|http://www.amchp.org/programsandtopics/family-engagement/SiteAssets/Pages/default/Family%20Engagement%20Case%20Study.pdf]\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[MCH Navigator, Georgetown University|https://www.mchnavigator.org/about/]\r\n[Maternal and Child Health Resources, HRSA|https://mchb.hrsa.gov/]\r\n[Family Engagement, Association of Maternal and Child Health Programs|http://www.amchp.org/programsandtopics/family-engagement/Pages/default.aspx]\r\n','Organizational Administrative Competencies intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health'),('OUTER','ACCOUNTABILITY','Accountability and Performance Management focus on continuous quality improvement in the public health system. Agencies should be able to perform according to accepted business standards and in compliance with local, state and federal policies, laws and regulations. Agencies use evidence-based or promising practices, maintain an organization-wide culture of quality improvement, and use nationally recognized resources to monitor progress toward achieving organizational objectives. \r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_8b7dba9ddd1b49789d487cfff67e0c9e~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n - Ability to uphold accepted business standards and assume responsibility for public health actions in accordance with relevant local, state, and federal laws and policies\r\n - Ability to assure compliance with national and Public Health Accreditation Board Standards\r\n - Ability to develop and maintain a performance management system to monitor achievement of organizational objectives\r\n - Ability to continuously evaluate and improve organizational processes, including using planning tools such as Plan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA) cycles\r\n - Ability to maintain an organization-wide culture of quality improvement using nationally recognized framework quality improvement tools and methods\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_f087d3f833f54801a6f42b33e3bd27d3.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Quality Improvement, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-infrastructure/performance-improvement/quality-improvement]\r\n[Quality Improvement, PHF|http://www.phf.org/focusareas/qualityimprovement/Pages/Quality_Improvement.aspx]\r\n[Quality Improvement Quick Guide, PHF|http://www.phf.org/focusareas/qualityimprovement/QIQuickGuide/Pages/Welcome_to_the_Guide_to_Quality_Improvement.aspx]\r\n[National Public Health Performance Standards, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/nphps/index.html]\r\n[Performance Management, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-infrastructure/performance-improvement/performance-management]\r\n[Performance Management Toolkit, PHF|http://www.phf.org/focusareas/performancemanagement/toolkit/Pages/Performance_Management_Toolkit.aspx]\r\n[PHAB Standards and Measures, PHAB|https://phaboard.org/wp-content/uploads/PHABSM_WEB_LR1-1.pdf]\r\n[Why Become Accredited, PHAB|https://phaboard.org/why-become-accredited/]\r\n[Reaping the Benefits of Accreditation Across the Nation, PHAB|https://phaboard.org/2019/02/28/the-benefits-of-accreditation-across-the-nation/]\r\n[MICH Accreditation Standards, MICH|http://michweb.org/accreditation-standards/]','Accountability and Performance Management'),('OUTER','ASSESSMENT','Assessment and Surveillance include the ability to collect, access, analyze and use data to guide public health planning and decision making. It includes the ability to prioritize and respond to data requests, translate data into understandable reports, consider data through the lens of health equity and social determinants of health, and use data to identify local, regional and state public health priorities.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_cd199acec76d473f863d62dac3091bcb~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n- Describes factors affecting the health of a community (e.g. equity, income, education, environment)\r\n - Identifies/Determines quantitative and qualitiative data and information needed for assessing the health of a community\r\n - Applies/Ensures ethical principles are applied in accessing, collecting, analyszing, using, maintaining, and disseminating data and information\r\n - Uses information technology in accessing, collecting, analyzing, using, maintaining, and disseminating data and information\r\n - Selects/Analyzes/Evaluates the validity and reliability of data\r\n - Selects/Analyzes/Evaluates the comparability of data (age-adjusted, variables, etc.)\r\n - Identifies/Resolves gaps in data\r\n - Collects/Ensures collection of valid and reliable quantitative and qualitative data\r\n - Describes applications/Analyzes/Determines trends from quantitative and qualitative data\r\n - Uses/Interprets/Integrates findings from quantitative and qualitiative data into organziational plans and operations\r\n - Describes/Identifies/Assesses assets and resources that can be used for improving the health of a community\r\n - Contributes to assessments/Assesses/Determines community health status and factors influencing health in a community\r\n - Explains/Develops/Ensures development of community health assessments using information about health status, factors influencing health, and assets and resources\r\n - Describes/Makes evidence-based decisions\r\n - Advocates for the use of evidence in decision making that affects the health of a community (helping elected officials understand health needs; demonstrating the impact of programs)\r\n - Recognizes/Determines/Explains limitations of evidence\r\n - Describes/Uses/Ensures the use of evidence in developing, implementing, evaluating, and improving policies, programs, and services\r\n - Describes, Identifies/Ensures the ethical conduct of research (based on laws, regulations, and procedures for ethical conduct of research)\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_827c21f293c749038b8a1ec8103df75d.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources: \r\n[Community Health Assessments and Health Improvement Plans, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/cha/plan.html]\r\n[Community Health Assessment Toolkit, Healthy Communities|https://www.healthycommunities.org/resources/community-health-assessment-toolkit]\r\n[Community Health Improvement Toolkit, Health Resources in Action|https://hria.org/resources/community-health-improvement-toolkit/]\r\n[Embracing Equity in Community Health Improvement, Health Resources in Action|https://hria.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Embracing-Equity-in-Community-Health-Improvement.pdf]\r\n[Community Health Assessment and Health Improvement Planning, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/cha/index.html]\r\n[Mobilizing for Action through Planning and Partnerships, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-infrastructure/performance-improvement/community-health-assessment/mapp]\r\n[Public Health Surveillance System, reference guide, Measure Evaluation|https://www.measureevaluation.org/resources/hisdatasourcesguide/module-10-public-health-surveillance-system]\r\n[Public Health Surveillance Activities, Johns Hopkins Medicine|https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/institutional_review_board/guidelines_policies/guidelines/public_health_surveillance_activities.html]\r\n[Uniform Chart of Accounts, PHAST|https://phastdata.org/research/chart-of-accounts]\r\n[Data and Benchmarks, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealthgateway/cha/data.html]\r\n[Training:  Introduction to Public Health Surveillance, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/publichealth101/surveillance.html]','Assessment and Surveillance'),('OUTER','COMMUNICATIONS','Communications involves the sharing, receiving, and interpretation of messages through a number of different techniques and pathways. Public health agencies should be able to write and implement an effective communication plan, execute risk communication strategies, and engage in two-way communication with internal and external audiences, including the media.\r\nSuccessful public health outcomes depend on an agencyâs ability to clearly communicate proactive health education and disease prevention messages. Agencies must assure information is accessible, understandable, and actionable for all audiences. Public health professionals should be equipped to act as ambassadors for public health, clearly articulating its reach and value.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_3c69ee9c1a5341f09b5f8d6819015b81~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n - Identifies/Assesses/Ensures that the literacy of populations served is reflected in the organization\'s policies, programs, and services\r\n - Communicates in writing and orally with linguistic and cultural proficiency\r\n - Solicits input from/Ensures that the organization seeks input from other organizations and individuals for improving the health of a community\r\n - Suggests/Selects/Evaluates approaches for disseminating public health data and informatoin\r\n - Conveys data and information to professionals and the public using a variety of approaches\r\n - Communicates information/Evaluates strategies for communicating information to influence behavior and improve health (social marketing methods, Health Belief Model, Stages of Change model)\r\n - Facilitates communication among individuals, groups, and organizations\r\n - Describes/Communicates the roles of governmental public health, health care, and other partners in improving the health of a community\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_9506175649e04a09b8ee2a8a4b7a0254.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources: \r\n[Strategies for Developing Culturally Driven Public Health Communications, Public Health Communications Collaborative, 2023|https://publichealthcollaborative.org/resources/communications-tool-strategies-for-developing-culturally-driven-public-health-communications/?utm_source=PHCC+Email&utm_medium=email&utm_campaign=Newsletter&utm_content=DAFtI2EwDnw]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Becoming Better Messengers, The Network for Public Health Law|https://www.networkforphl.org/resources/topics/trainings/becoming-better-messengers/]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Plain Language for Public Health, Public Health Communications Collaborative, 2023|https://publichealthcollaborative.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/02/PHCC_Plain-Language-for-Public-Health.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Planning Before You Communicate, PHF|http://michweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Planning_Before_You_Communicate-1.xlsx]\r\n[Media/Communication Plan Template, CDC|http://michweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Communication-Plan-Template-BLANK_1.docx]\r\n[Message Framing, FrameWorks Institute|http://frameworksinstitute.org/assets/files/eZines/five_minute_refresher_ezine.pdf]\r\n[PHRASES: Using Message Framing Tools to Build and Sustain Cross-Sector Partnerships|https://www.r4phtc.org/phrases-using-message-framing-tools-to-build-and-sustain-cross-sector-partnerships/]\r\n[Answers to Tough Questions about Public Health, PHRASES|https://www.phrases.org/answers-to-tough-questions/]\r\n[Communication Resources, Public Health Communications Collaborative|https://publichealthcollaborative.org/]\r\n[Assessing Your Health Communication Plan, MICH|http://michweb.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Components-of-a-Health-Communications-Plan.pdf]\r\n[Health Literacy Friendly Principles|https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7mojA-U3G68&t=220s]\r\n[Joint Information System, FEMA|https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/20130726-1623-20490-0276/basic_guidance_for_pios_final_draft_12_06_07.pdf]\r\n[Health Equity Guiding Principles for Inclusive Communication, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/healthcommunication/HealthEquityGuidingPrinciples.pdf]','Communications'),('OUTER','COMMUNITY','Public health agencies should be able to create, convene, and sustain strategic collaborative relationships with local, state, and regional partners, in keeping with the Public Health 3.0 model. Acting as their community\'s chief health strategist, agencies should have the ability to build trust andÂ engage communities in strategic, evidence-based community health improvement initiatives. Guided by data, these initiatives should address health inequitiesÂ and social determinants of health. \r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_4a6430ffef734f359f6bac0942402340~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n - Ability to create and maintain strategic, non-program-specific relationships with key community partners (i.e. health care organizations, governmental agencies, community groups, private businesses.)\r\n - Ability to coordinate governmental public health efforts at the local level through dialog, periodic meetings, and leadership provided by the LPHA\r\n - Ability to mobilize key community partners to support development of public health policies\r\n - Ability to maintain trust with and engage community residents at the grassroots level\r\n - Ability to strategically select governmental public health roles in programmatic and policy activities\r\n - Ability to articulate governmental public health roles in programmatic and policy activities to key community partners\r\n - Ability to convene a broad, multi-sector assembly of public health and medical stakeholders to promote health, prevent disease, and protect residents within the community\r\n - Ability to engage community members to develop and implement community health improvement plans to address priorities identified in health assessments\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_8feb81dc58f94cac85308b4014abddc7.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources: \r\n[Communities of Excellence Framework, Communities of Excellence 2026|https://communitiesofexcellence2026.org/what-we-do/framework.html]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Partnering with Residents, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/learning-guides/partnering-with-residents#/]\r\n[Clinical to Community Connections|https://www.astho.org/Programs/Health-Systems-Transformation/]\r\n[Creating and Maintaining Coalitions and Partnerships, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/creating-and-maintaining-coalitions-and-partnerships]\r\n[The Community Canvas Guidebook, Community Canvas|https://github.com/communitycanvas/documents/raw/master/CommunityCanvas-Guidebook.pdf?loc=heading]\r\n[Chief Health Strategist Competency Assessment, NACCHO|https://virtualcommunities.naccho.org/HigherLogic/System/DownloadDocumentFile.ashx?DocumentFileKey=af13b42a-a36d-af5b-fd90-d5299b4f019b&forceDialog=0]\r\n[Chief Health Strategist Competencies, NACCHO|https://virtualcommunities.naccho.org/HigherLogic/System/DownloadDocumentFile.ashx?DocumentFileKey=91439585-9f89-9ea6-57ee-486258d5fc45&forceDialog=0]\r\n[Partner Center, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/take-action-to-improve-health/partner-center]\r\n[Effective Coalition Member Recruitment, County Health Rankings and Roadmaps|https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/sites/default/files/media/document/EffectiveRecruitmentCoalition.pdf]\r\n[Tips for Engaging Businesses as Public Health Partners, Journal of Public Health Management and Practice|https://journals.lww.com/jphmp/fulltext/2019/09000/tips_for_engaging_local_businesses_as_public.16.aspx]\r\n[Good Health is Good Business, deBeaumont|https://www.debeaumont.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Good-Health-Is-Good-Business.pdf]\r\n','Community Partnership Development'),('OUTER','EMERGENCY','Natural disasters, emerging infectious diseases, and the potential for rapid spread of communicable diseases require that public health agencies maintain a high level of preparedness for emergency response. All public health agencies should have the ability to lead their local public health emergency response and assure communication among all Emergency Support Function 8 - Public Health and Medical organizations. Agencies should be able to issue and enforce emergency health orders, share key information with partners and the general public, and promote ongoing community resilience and preparedness.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_12ac22f34ac04a4fb1a6211a6cefd335~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n  - Ability to develop and rehearse public health emergency response strategies and plans\r\n - Ability to address needs of vulnerable populations during a public health emergency\r\n - Ability to lead the Emergency Support Function 8 â Public Health and Medical for the jurisdiction\r\n - Ability to activate emergency response personnel in the event of a public health emergency\r\n - Ability to coordinate with emergency response partners from both private and ?governmental sectors\r\n - Ability to lead emergency response utilizing the National Incident Management system, as well as any local emergency response processes during a public health emergency\r\n - Ability to maintain a continuity of operations plan (COOP)\r\n - Ability to access to financial resources to execute emergency responses\r\n - Ability to promote community preparedness through communication with the public before, during, or after a disaster\r\n - Ability to issue emergency health orders via statutory authority\r\n - Ability to enforce emergency health orders via statutory authority\r\n - Ability to be notified of public health emergencies on a 24/7 basis\r\n - Ability to respond to public health emergencies on a 24/7 basis\r\n - Ability to utilize and support the Missouri Laboratory Response Network (MOLRN) for identification of biological and chemical threats\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_8f63ffc35c3a4a6f8254892a3f8dba63.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Cybersecurity Mitigation Guide: Healthcare and Public Health Sector, CISA|https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/2023-12/HPH-Sector-Mitigation-Guide-TLP-CLEAR._508c.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[CDCâs Public Health Emergency Preparedness Program: Every Response is Local, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/cpr/whatwedo/phep.htm]\r\n[Public Health Emergency Preparedness and Response Capabilities, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/cpr/readiness/toolsandresources.htm]\r\n[Public Health Preparedness, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-preparedness]\r\n[Community Resilience, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-preparedness/community-resilience]\r\n[Administrative Preparedness Legal Guidebook, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/programs/public-health-preparedness/systems-preparedness/administrative-preparedness-legal-guidebook]\r\n[Capacity-Building Toolkit for Including Aging and Disability Networks in Emergency Planning, NACCHO|https://www.naccho.org/uploads/downloadable-resources/Capacity-Building-Toolkit-for-Aging-and-Disability-Networks-2-5-19.pdf]\r\n[Legal Preparedness Webinar Series, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/cpr/partnerships/webinars.htm]\r\n[Education, Training and Planning Resources, CDC|https://www.cdc.gov/cpr/training.htm]\r\n[Ensuring Equity in COVID-19 Planning, Response, and Recovery Decision-Making, Human Impact Partners|https://humanimpact.org/hipprojects/ensuring-equity-in-covid-19-planning-response-and-recovery-decision-making/]','Emergency Preparedness and Response'),('OUTER','ORGANIZATION','In order to deliver foundational public health programs and services, public health agencies should achieve competency in cross-cutting organizational administrative skills such as leadership and governance, information technology, human resources services, legal services, financial management, contract and procurement services, and facilities and operations management. Agencies should demonstrate competency advocating for the role of governmental public health, leveraging funding, defending budgets, incorporating ethical standards, assuring continuous quality improvement, using performance management systems, developing employees, adjusting to shifts in culture and environment, and managing change.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_f2879cc1e917445e9e6a7534c493a032~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n - Ability to lead internal and external stakeholders to consensus and in action planning\r\n - Ability to serve as the public face of governmental public health in the community\r\n - Ability to strategically coordinate health equity programming relevant to the LPHAâs communities served\r\n - Ability to act as a resource to support health equity work across the department\r\n - Ability to support, maintain, and use electronic communication technology\r\n - Ability to maintain and access electronic health information to support the public health agencyâs operations and analyze health data\r\n - Ability to have proper systems in place to keep protected health information (PHI) and confidential organizational data restricted\r\n - Ability to recruit and retain a competent public health workforce with considerations for succession planning\r\n - Ability to deliver workforce training\r\n - Ability to engage in and document workforce performance review\r\n - Ability to comply with federal, state, and local fiscal standards and policies regarding fiscal management, contract, and procurement services\r\n - Ability to perform accounting activities including payroll, accounts receivable, general ledger, chart of accounts, and accounts payable\r\n - Ability to manage all contracts providing services for the agency, including pass-through dollars to consultants and other public and private organizations\r\n - Ability to manage all grants/contracts bringing money into the agency, including monitoring the compliance with state, federal, and sponsor requirements for the use of the dollars\r\n - Ability to procure, maintain, and manage safe facilities to support agency operations\r\n - Ability to access and appropriately use legal services in planning and implementing public health initiatives\r\n - Ability to voluntarily pursue public health agency accreditation via the Public Health Accreditation Board (PHAB) or Missouri Institute for Community Health (MICH)\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_5933a304d3f7473da297db9b62d12a8d.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources: \r\n[Framework for Workplace Mental Health and Well-Being, US Surgeon General, 2022|https://www.hhs.gov/sites/default/files/workplace-mental-health-well-being.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Trauma-Informed Workplaces: Concepts, Strategies, and Tactics to Build Workplaces that Support Well-Being (toolkit), Campaign for Trauma Informed Policy and Practice|https://www.ctipp.org/post/toolkit-trauma-informed-workplaces]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Public Health 3.0 Call to Action|https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2017/17_0017.htm]\r\n[Case Study: Collaborating for Improved Information Technology Services in Florida|https://phsharing.org/success-stories/collaborating-for-improved-information-technology-services/]\r\n[Training: Public Health Administration/Management Courses, Heartland Center|https://www.heartland-lms.com/public-health-administration-management]\r\n[Organizational SOAR Analysis|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Gearbox/SOAR_Administrative_Organizational_Competencies.pdf]\r\n[Quality Improvement in Public Health, Public Health Foundation|http://www.phf.org/focusareas/qualityimprovement/Pages/Quality_Improvement.aspx]\r\n[Improving Organizational Management and Development, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/improve-organizational-management-and-development]','Organizational Administrative Competencies'),('OUTER','POLICY','Policies are essential to improve the physical, environmental, social and economic conditions that affect health. Policy Development and Support indicate that every public health agency should have the ability to serve as an expert resource for establishing, maintaining and developing basic public health policy recommendations that are evidence-based, grounded in law and legally defendable. Public health agencies should be able to effectively inform and influence policies being considered by other organizations in their jurisdiction.\r\n[Current Local Public Health Capacity|https://static.wixstatic.com/media/9bd019_a76c1baa52da4036b9ba567e48e82253~mv2.jpg]\r\n\r\nFoundational Capacities:\r\n - Ability to develop evidence-based and legally feasible public health policy recommendations for legislative decision-makers\r\n - Ability to include the needs of vulnerable populations within recommendations for public health policies\r\n - Ability to research, analyze, cost out, and articulate the impact of public health policy recommendations\r\n - Ability to organize support for public health policy recommendations and place them before an entity with the legal authority to adopt them\r\n - Ability to work with partners and policymakers to enact policies that are evidence-based and that address the social determinants of health\r\n\r\n[Gearbox: Guide to Increasing Capacity|https://www.healthiermo.org/_files/ugd/9bd019_02e6ed1d2afd4a3292e6b6e034ccc566.pdf]\r\n\r\nAdditional Resources:\r\n[Congressional District Health Dashboard, NYU Langone Health|https://www.congressionaldistricthealthdashboard.org/] &nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Proactive Rental Inspections Sample Policy, ChangeLab Solutions, 2023|https://www.changelabsolutions.org/product/model-proactive-rental-inspection-ordinance?utm_source=ChangeLab+Solutions+Active&utm_campaign=5b41758dac-PRI-Model-Poli_Launch_0923&utm_medium=email&utm_term=0_-5b41758dac-%5BLIST_EMAIL_ID%5D]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Undoing the Drivers of Health Inequity, Change Lab Solutions|https://www.changelabsolutions.org/drivers-health-inequity]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Strategies for Equitable Policymaking: Applying Law and Policy Frameworks to Improve Health, ChangeLab Solutions, 2023|https://www.changelabsolutions.org/sites/default/files/2023-06/Strategies-for-Equitable-Policymaking_FINAL_20230620A.pdf]&nbsp;&nbsp;<font color=red>NEW!</font color>\r\n[Health in All Policies, ASTHO|https://www.astho.org/Programs/Prevention/Implementing-the-National-Prevention-Strategy/HiAP-Toolkit/]\r\n[Why We Need Health-Informed Policies and Decision-Making (2011), National Research Council|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK83538/]\r\n[Understanding Evidence-Based Public Health Policy (2009), AJPH|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2724448/?&sa=U&ei=ZymPVJ6dPMP1oASN44C4Aw&ved=0CHcQFjAR&usg=AFQjCNHkpuJ_0YJICbKHuQrnRFA10ARqEg]\r\n[Influencing Policy Development, Community Tool Box|https://ctb.ku.edu/en/influencing-policy-development]\r\n[Public Health and Prevention, Alliance for Health Policy|http://www.allhealthpolicy.org/sourcebook/public-health-and-prevention/]\r\n[Pain in the Nation (policies to address Drug, Alcohol and Suicide Crises), Trust for Americaâs Health|https://www.tfah.org/report-details/pain-in-the-nation/]\r\n[Healing the Nation: Advancing Mental Health & Addiction Policy, Well Being Trust|https://wellbeingtrust.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/WBT_Healing-the-Nation-digital.pdf]\r\n[COVID-19 Policy Playbook II: Legal Recommendations for a Safer, More Equitable Future|Public Health Law]\r\n\r\n','Policy Development and Support'),('POLICY','CHRONIC','In December 2019, President Trump raised the federal minimum age for tobacco purchases to 21, by signing legislation that amended the Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act. Tobacco use remains the leading cause of death in the US, and 96% of current tobacco users began smoking or using other tobacco products before the age of 21.\r\nIn Missouri [2,200 children under 18 years old become new daily smokers each year|https://www.tobaccofreekids.org/problem/toll-us/missouri]. Approximately [128,000 Missouri youth will ultimately die prematurely from smoking|https://www.tobaccofreekids.org/problem/toll-us/missouri]. The [Institutes of Medicine|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK310412/pdf/Bookshelf_NBK310412.pdf] estimate that Tobacco 21 legislation will keep one in four teens age 15 - 17 from starting tobacco use, and will reduce tobacco initiation by 15% in youth age 18 - 20.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nThe city of [Springfield|https://www.springfieldmo.gov/4960/Tobacco-21#:~:text=Tobacco%2021%E2%80%94a%20Springfield%20ordinance,into%20effect%20July%2016%2C%202019.] took action ahead of the federal legislative change, working with community partners to collect evidence and build the case for local adoption of a Tobacco 21 ordinance. Springfield City Council [voted to adopt the ordinance|https://healthiermo.org/pdf/Stories/072619_Tobacco_21_SGCHD.pdf] in July 2019. \r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Tobacco 21|https://tobacco21.org/]\r\n[Tobacco 21, FDA|https://www.fda.gov/tobacco-products/retail-sales-tobacco-products/tobacco-21#2]\r\n[Tobacco 21: An Easy Way to Save Young Lives (fact sheet), AAP|https://www.aap.org/en-us/advocacy-and-policy/aap-health-initiatives/Richmond-Center/Documents/Tobacco21Handout.pdf]','Policy Development intersect with Chronic Disease Prevention'),('POLICY','COMMUNICABLE_DISEASE','As early as the eighteenth century, policies have been put in place to control the spread of communicable diseases. American port cities established rules for isolation of the sick, and Massachusetts passed laws for isolation of people with smallpox. Public health agencies continue to establish policies to isolate the sick and quarantine the exposed in order to prevent the spread of disease. Additional policies - like those addressing safe food handling practices - seek to protect public health by mitigating the spread of diseases and preventing disease outbreaks.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nDuring the height of the COVID pandemic, community transmission and testing delays led to a high number of cases in some communities in Missouri. Local jursidictions passed [ordinances requiring residents to wear face masks|https://westplains.net/new/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Ordinance-4672-Face-Covering-Ordinance.pdf] when outside of their own homes. These policies reduced COVID-19 transmission from symptomatic and asymptomatic persons.\r\nA large [outbreak of hepatitis A|https://health.mo.gov/news/newsitem/uuid/ac4db9a0-01ae-4b1b-b550-83c36f998fa4] in 35 Missouri counties between 2017 - 2019 led to 233 hospitalizations and two deaths.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Creating a Coronavirus Mask Policy for Work, Paycor|https://www.paycor.com/resource-center/coronavirus-mask-policy-work-template]\r\n[OSHA Recommends Mandatory Face Masks at Work, OSHA|https://www.osha.gov/SLTC/covid-19/]\r\n','Policy Development intersect with Communicable Disease Control'),('POLICY','ENVIRONMENT','Environmental public health focuses on the relationships between people and their environment. Public health professionals work with partners to create policies that promote healthy and safe communities. These include policies to reduce chemicals, contaminants, and environmental exposures in order to assure safe air, water, soil and food. Common policies address food safety, wastewater containment and disposal, smoke-free air, asbestos abatement, lead abatement, and sanitation.\r\n\r\nCase Study:\r\nThe [drinking water crisis in Flint, Michigan|https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5353852/] shows the impact environmental health issues can have on vulnerable populations, as people living in under-resourced neighborhoods had the most significant exposure to drinking water contaminated with lead.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Missouri Food Code|https://health.mo.gov/safety/foodsafety/pdf/missourifoodcode.pdf]\r\n[Onsite Wastewater Treatment Regulations, DHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/environment/onsite/lawsregs.php]\r\n[Missouri Clean Indoor Air Statutes|https://health.mo.gov/living/wellness/tobacco/smokingandtobacco/pdf/Missouri_CIA_Statutes.pdf]\r\n[Lead Policy and Guidance, EPA|https://www.epa.gov/lead/lead-policy-and-guidance]\r\n','Policy Development intersect with Environmental Public Health'),('POLICY','INJURY','According to the Missouri Department of Transportation (MODOT), motor vehicle accidents are the leading cause of death for Missouri children. Nearly 3 in 4 children are not properly restrained in car seats or by seat belts, leaving them at risk of injury or death in a car crash.\r\nMissouri state statute [RSMO 307.179|https://revisor.mo.gov/main/OneSection.aspx?section=307.179#:~:text=307.179.,%E2%80%94%201.&text=(2)%20%22Child%20passenger%20restraint,set%20forth%20in%2049%20C.F.R.] requires that children under 16 years old be secured in a seat belt or in a child safety seat appropriate for their age and weight.\r\n[Safe Kids Missouri|https://www.safekids.org/coalition/safe-kids-missouri#:~:text=Safe%20Kids%20Missouri%20is%20led,goal%3A%20keeping%20your%20kids%20safe.], [MODOT|https://www.modot.org/booster-seats#:~:text=Children%20ages%204%20through%207,into%20an%20appropriate%20booster%20seat.], local fire departments, and local public health agencies work together to help parents choose the right car seat, provide free car seats, offer installation guidance and inspections at no cost to parents.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Car Seat Installation Inspection Sites in Missouri|https://safekids.org/inspection-stations#MO]\r\n[Car Seats and Booster Seats: Choosing the right car seat for your child, NHTSA|https://www.nhtsa.gov/equipment/car-seats-and-booster-seats]\r\n[Safe Kids Coalitions in Missouri|https://health.mo.gov/living/families/injuries/safekids.php#:~:text=Safe%20Kids%20Missouri%2C%20led%20by,common%20goal%3A%20keeping%20kids%20safe.]\r\n[National Child Passenger Safety (CPS) Training, Safe Kids Worldwide|https://cert.safekids.org/]\r\n','Policy Development intersect with Injury Prevention'),('POLICY','LINKAGE','Policies to adopt a screening process during client encounters can help public health professionals more readily identify referral needs. A strong public health system depends on collaborative partnerships with healthcare, mental health, behavioral health, oral health, and many other service providers in a community. Public health agencies are tasked with convening everyone who has a role in community health to foster networks that encourage referrals.','Policy Development intersect with Linkage to Medical, Behavioral, and Community Resources'),('POLICY','MATERNAL','The American Academy of Pediatrics outlines the [benefits of breastfeeding|https://www.aap.org/en-us/advocacy-and-policy/aap-health-initiatives/Breastfeeding/Pages/Benefits-of-Breastfeeding.aspx] for both mother and infant. Studies show mothers who choose to breastfeed are more successful when they have community support.\r\nIn 2010, the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act amended Section 7 of the Labor Standards Act to require employers to provide [reasonable break time and a private space|https://www.dol.gov/agencies/whd/nursing-mothers], other than a bathroom, for employee to express breast milk for her nursing child.\r\nThe Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services (MoDHSS) partners with the [Missouri Breastfeeding Coalition|http://www.mobreastfeeding.org/] and local public health agencies to educate employers on the federal policy and the value of supporting lactating mothers in the workplace.\r\n\r\nResources:\r\n[Breastfeeding Friendly Worksite Program, MoDHSS|https://health.mo.gov/living/families/wic/breastfeeding/worksiteinitiatives/#:~:text=The%20Missouri%20Breastfeeding%20Friendly%20Worksite,businesses%20that%20support%20their%20breastfeeding] \r\n[Business Case for Breastfeeding, US DHHS|https://www.womenshealth.gov/breastfeeding/breastfeeding-home-work-and-public/breastfeeding-and-going-back-work/business-case]','Policy Development intersect with Maternal, Child, and Family Health');
